docs.abstract: Players and coaches knelt before the national anthem, and teams played a message of unity at the first two games of the 2020 season.
docs.snippet: Players and coaches knelt before the national anthem, and teams played a message of unity at the first two games of the 2020 season.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The 200-yard black cloth stretched along the foul lines, starting at one edge of the outfield, wrapping around home plate and extending to the other side of the diamond. It was held by coaches and players from both the Washington Nationals and the Yankees, all spaced out, as a message recorded by the actor Morgan Freeman played over the stadium speakers.

headline.main: On Opening Day, a Rarity for M.L.B.: Support for Black Lives Matter
headline.print_headline: Baseball, Latecomer on Social Issues, Honors Black Lives Matter on Opening Day

docs.abstract: A tempest over the band Blackpink’s use of a Hindu god in a video was the latest example of K-pop fans holding artists to account — while staying fiercely loyal.
docs.snippet: A tempest over the band Blackpink’s use of a Hindu god in a video was the latest example of K-pop fans holding artists to account — while staying fiercely loyal.
docs.lead_paragraph: The statue of the Hindu god Ganesha flashed onscreen for just seconds in the music video by Blackpink, an all-female K-pop band. The elephant-headed deity was shown on the floor, near a bejeweled Aladdin lamp, as a member of the band preened and rapped on a golden throne.

headline.main: Hindu God in a Music Video? A K-Pop Band Runs Afoul of Fans
headline.print_headline: Hindu God in a Video?  Fans of a K-Pop Band  Force Quick Re-editing

docs.abstract: The pandemic has been brutal to buskers. It’s even harder when you have to haul a Steinway all over New York City.
docs.snippet: The pandemic has been brutal to buskers. It’s even harder when you have to haul a Steinway all over New York City.
docs.lead_paragraph: Colin Huggins, the piano man of Washington Square Park, sat at his Steinway baby grand the other day playing one of Claude Debussy’s frolicking arabesques. A few onlookers wore surgical masks and listened from benches. Elsewhere in the park, a Black Lives Matter protest was starting and a worker climbed up a ladder to scrub away graffiti from the Washington Arch.

headline.main: It’s a Tough Time to Be a Street Musician With a 900-Pound Piano
headline.print_headline: Hard Times for the Piano Man of Washington Sq. Park
